What is RDS in AWS?

🧠 What AWS handles for you
Server setup
OS patching
Database installation
Backups                     ---    Daily backups + point-in-time recovery
Scaling                     ---    Vertical scaling (increase CPU/RAM) , Storage auto scaling
High availability           ---    Automatically creates standby DB in another zone

👉 So you don’t need to manually install MySQL/PostgreSQL on EC2.

📦 Supported Databases

RDS supports:

MySQL
PostgreSQL
MariaDB
Oracle
SQL Server
Amazon Aurora (AWS own DB)

RDS is a managed relational database service in AWS that handles database setup, backups, patching, and scaling, allowing us to focus on application development instead of infrastructure.


Difference between RDS & DynamoDB?

Example: Banking app (accounts, transactions)

RDS (Relational Database Service)
Type: Relational (SQL)
Structure: Tables, rows, columns
Schema: Fixed (predefined)
Query Language: SQL
Examples: MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle


DynamoDB
Type: NoSQL (key-value / document)
Structure: Flexible (no fixed schema)
Schema: Dynamic
Query Language: No SQL (API-based)
Fully serverless

Example:
Gaming apps
Leaderboards, player sessions
E-commerce (high traffic parts)
Shopping cart, user sessions
Social media apps
Likes, comments, feeds
